# Copy to .env.local and fill in to flip the app to live MCP mode.
# Without this token, every UI flow runs against a curated mock catalog —
# badges read "⚪ Demo data". Set the token and the same routes hit
# mcp.swiggy.com/food for real Swiggy data — badges flip to
# "🟢 Live · Swiggy MCP".
#
# Two ways to get the token:
#
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Path A — Consumer track (fast, available today, no application needed)
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Swiggy's Consumer install runs the OAuth 2.1 PKCE flow via `mcp-remote`,
# which caches the access token on disk. Steps:
#
#   1. Run once from a terminal:
#        npx mcp-remote https://mcp.swiggy.com/food
#
#      Browser opens → log in via phone + OTP → flow completes.
#
#   2. mcp-remote saves the token under your home directory (typically
#      ~/.mcp-auth/<server-hash>/access_token.json on macOS/Linux, or
#      %USERPROFILE%\.mcp-auth\... on Windows). Open that file and copy
#      the `access_token` value.
#
#   3. Paste it below (no "Bearer " prefix — the client adds it).
#
# Note: the Consumer install is intended for use *inside* an MCP client
# like Claude Desktop. Reusing the token in a separate web app technically
# works (it's the same OAuth bearer) but check Swiggy's TOS before doing
# this in anything user-facing.
#
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Path B — Developer track (proper, takes days)
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. Apply at https://mcp.swiggy.com/builders/access (Developer track).
#   2. After approval, you receive an OAuth client_id; complete the PKCE
#      flow described at https://mcp.swiggy.com/builders/docs/start/authenticate.md
#   3. Paste the returned access_token below.
#
SWIGGY_MCP_TOKEN=
